<h3>
    Gear &amp; Lure Suggestions
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rod:</strong> 6’6″–7′ medium-heavy casting rod
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Line:</strong> 12–17 lb braid with 10–12 lb fluorocarbon leader
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Lures:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Topwater: frogs, poppers (spring/summer)
            </li>
            <li>
                Soft plastics: Senkos, creature baits near cover
            </li>
            <li>
                Spinnerbaits/crankbaits: spring spawn &amp; fall feeding
            </li>
            <li>
                Jigs &amp; finesse worms: winter structure fishing
            </li>
            <li>
                Jerkbaits &amp; soft craws: Willamette River smallmouth area
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Pro Tips for Local Bass Fishing
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Kayak Advantage:</strong> Helps access pockets in Hagg Lake, sloughs, and Estacada.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Target Structure:</strong> Vegetation, docks, riprap, rocky points, and creek mouths.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Practice Catch &amp; Release:</strong> Especially for tournament bass and larger specimens.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Stay Informed:</strong> Check ODFW bag limits – 5 fish/day, max 3 over 15″ in Willamette Zone
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    FAQs
</h3>
<p>
    <strong>Q1: What’s the best all-around nearby spot?</strong><br>
    Henry Hagg Lake for largemouth; Willamette River for smallmouth.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q2: Any good beginner urban ponds?</strong><br>
    Try Hartman Pond or St. Louis Ponds—they’re small, accessible, and fish well.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q3: Can I fish from shore?</strong><br>
    Yes! All spots have bank access; boats increase range but aren’t necessary.
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q4: Are there size/game restrictions?</strong><br>
    Yes—ODFW sets 5 bass/day, with only 3 over 15″ in Willamette Zone
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q5: Is eating bass safe here?</strong><br>
    Avoid consumption from Portland Harbor and Columbia Slough due to contaminants&nbsp;
</p>
<p>
    <strong>Q6: When is topwater best?</strong><br>
    Spring mornings and summer dawn/dusk produce explosive topwater action.
</p>
<p>
    &nbsp;
</p>
<h3>
    Final Thoughts
</h3>
<p>
    From trophy largemouth in Hagg Lake to solid smallmouth runs in the Willamette and slough systems, <strong>bass fishing near Portland</strong> offers diversity and adventure—all within an hour's radius. Whether you're casting off a dock or paddling a kayak, there's always a bass chase waiting.
</p>
<p>
    Tight lines and happy fishing!
</p>

